entry.title: Fix non-device ChromeOS chrome::DIR_CRASH_DUMPS
entry.content:
This restricts use of /var/log/{chrome,lacros} for DIR_CRASH_DUMPS to

IS_CHROMEOS_DEVICE builds. This lets us use DIR_CRASH_DUMPS on a local

linux-chromeos build. Providing a value for chrome::DIR_CRASH_DUMPS is

necessary for initializing crashpad. Without this change a local

is_chromeos build will fail if --enable-crashpad is provided.



Fixing this is necessary to ultimately remove --enable-crashpad (and

default it to true) without breaking local development and bots that

don't run on device. Looks like local development was still using the

breakpad flow.



Bug: 1520868

currently on the initial empty document, but the initiator origin is

not the parent's origin, e.g. if it's started by another ancestor frame

or child frames. In this case, don't categorize the navigations as

synchronous about:blank navigations.

entry.title: Introduce devtools_instrumentation::WillCreateURLLoaderFactoryParams
entry.content:
Preparation for

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/5150529

and subsequent CLs to merge `devtools_instrumentation` call sites,

so that the unified method `url_loader_factory::Create()`

can invoke `devtools_instrumentation`

by `WillCreateURLLoaderFactoryParams::Run()`,

while the callers of `url_loader_factory::Create()`

create context-specific `WillCreateURLLoaderFactoryParams`,

instead of calling context-specific `WillCreateURLLoaderFactory*()`

methods directly.



This CL makes some callers to pass non-null `factory_chainer`

(for uniformity) where `nullptr` was used previously.

This doesn't change the behavior, because those callers pass

non-null FactoryOverride, and in such cases `factory_chainer` is

anyway not used.



Bug: 1506871

entry.content:

Docking Promo can be displayed via new utils helper,

CanShowDockingPromo().

3. Introduces DockingPromoMediator which determines whether or not the

Docking Promo can be displayed, and queues the promo for Remind Me Later

if pressed. Also, includes unit tests.

entry.title: Stop using process privilege buckets for extensions.
entry.content:
These are mostly unnecessary now that all extensions require locked

processes, and their remaining use cases can be replaced with

alternate checks. This CL moves their use behind a kill switch feature

(StopUsingRenderProcessHostPrivilege). Namely,

RenderProcessHostPrivilege, GetProcessPrivilege() and

GetPrivilegeRequiredByUrl() all become dead code and can be removed

once this CL is verified not to cause problems in the wild.



The buckets, defined by the RenderProcessHostPrivilege enum, were used

in two places:



1. In ChromeContentBrowserClientExtensionsPart::CanCommitURL(), which

is checked at DidCommitNavigation time to verify that a navigation

commit was valid (terminating the renderer otherwise). There's a

workaround that allows an extension URL to commit in any

PRIV_EXTENSION process, even if that process's ProcessMap entry

doesn't match the committing extension ID (e.g., extension A is

allowed to commit in extension B's process). This was for an old bug

(crbug.com/840857) that predated strict site isolation and strict

extension isolation, and it's highly likely that this is no longer

needed. A DumpWithoutCrashing was added to confirm this in r1239949,

and so far there haven't been any DWOC reports in one month since it

landed (see crbug.com/840857 for details). This CL turns this

workaround off (behind a kill switch).



2. In ChromeContentBrowserClientExtensionsPart::IsSuitableHost(),

which is checked when picking a SiteInstance and a process for a

navigation, to ensure that a navigation can only commit in a process

with a matching privilege bucket. This is generally a less strict

check than site isolation, since it only ensures separation between

the three privilege buckets (all extensions, all hosted apps, all web

sites), but does not check process reuse within each bucket, unlike

core site isolation checks that compare actual process locks (e.g., in

RenderProcessHostImpl::IsSuitableHost(), just prior to calling

ChromeContentBrowserClientExtensionsPart::IsSuitableHost()). However,

the privilege bucket check does have subtle use cases not covered by

core site isolation checks:



(i) It does not allow a hosted app loaded from https://foo.com to reuse

a process of a regular web page loaded from https://foo.com (e.g.,

when one URL is in the hosted app's extent but a second same-site URL

is not, or when reloading a tab after disabling or re-enabling the

hosted app). There are various tests covering this, including

ProcessManagementTest.ProcessOverflow,

AppApiTest.NavigateIntoAppProcess, AppApiTest.ReloadIntoAppProcess*,

and other tests in AppApiTest.



(ii) It does not allow an extension URL loaded for a disabled extension

to share a process with an extension URL loaded after re-enabling the

extension. This is covered by

DisableExtensionBrowserTest.VisitReenabledExtensionInSubframe.



This CL proposes a different way to do these checks, without relying

on process privilege buckets. Namely, the extensions ProcessMap

already tracks whether a given process is used for particular

extensions or hosted apps, and processes that load disabled

extensions/app URLs are *not* entered into the ProcessMap. So, both

(i) and (ii) above can be handled by checking that (1) a

chrome-extension://extid/ URL can only commit in a process P that's

registered in the ProcessMap for that extension (i.e., has an entry

{extid, P}), and (2) a non-extension URL cannot use a process that's

registered in the ProcessMap for any extension.



This CL replaces the IsSuitableHost privilege bucket checks with these

two new checks, keeping the old path around behind a kill switch as a

precaution. This approach more closely matches the existing checks [1]

in CanCommitURL(), which are already based on ProcessMap. Since

IsSuitableHost() is provided with a target site URL that's computed

after resolving effective URLs, this works for both extensions and

hosted apps. A URL loaded in a hosted app won't be allowed to share a

process with a same-site non-app URL, since the former will get

resolved to a chrome-extension: site URL, with a process that's

registered in ProcessMap, while the latter won't have a

chrome-extension: site URL, with a process that's not registered in

ProcessMap.



This CL builds on creis@'s earlier work in

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4127610,

taking a slightly stricter approach of using ProcessMap-based checks

instead of checking that the extension process should be locked (which

should already be checked earlier in RPHI::IsSuitableHost()). This

also handles the disabled extension cases and allows us to remove the

hosted app bucket.



There is one known behavior difference caused by the new ProcessMap

checks in this CL. Previously, two hosted apps loaded from different

parts of the same site (e.g., from https://app.com/app1/app1.html and

https://app.com/app2/app2.html) were allowed to share a process (e.g.,

when over the process limit), since they ended up with the same

process lock (https://app.com) and the same privilege bucket

(PRIV_HOSTED). The new ProcessMap checks are stricter and only allow

an extension X to use a process registered in the ProcessMap

specifically for X and not another extension. Hence, the process reuse

in the above scenario is no longer allowed - only instances of the

same app are allowed to share a process. This behavior should be more

secure and shouldn't actually cause any breakage, since we wouldn't

normally reuse a process for these apps unless we were over the

process limit. This is covered by one of the cases in

ProcessManagementTest.ProcessOverflow.

entry.title: Speculative fix for RenderLoop::ExitPresent crash
entry.content:
It looks as though (at least on Android), it's possible for ExitPresent

to be called in response to a StopRuntime call. The JavaHandlerThread

appears to teardown/destroy the task_runner before the StopRuntime call

thus resulting in a crash. It does look as though base::Thread does not

tear down the task_runner before this point, but StopRuntime is already

resilient to re-entrant calls, such that it doesn't seem worth investing

in a more complete fix to fully avoid that further re-entrant behavior.

entry.title: [Win-a11y] Fix incorrect bounding rect in web content
entry.content:
On all platforms, the accessible nodes coming from web content compute

their bounding rectangle in screen physical coordinates by scaling the

bounds it gets in screen DIPs from the window by the device scale factor.

This is incorrect on Windows.



On Windows, we must use the display::win::ScreenWin::DIPToScreenRect

function to apply correctly the device scale factor. This is what we're

already doing for accessible node coming from Views, and what we're

doing essentially everywhere we need to send a rect or a point to a

Windows API, like in the TSF Store. We just weren't doing the same for

accessible nodes coming from web content.



My understanding of why we can't perform a plain DSF scale operation on

Windows is limited, but here's what I got from debugging the area:



* Windows first sends the display information to Chromium. At this

point, we have what I think we call "screen pixels" coordinates.

I'll call them Windows-POV-screen-physical-coordinates here.

* Windows has been historically bad at handling set ups of multiple

monitors of different DPI, so we run our own logic to ensure Chromium

renders correctly on every monitor. This leads us to create our own

internal representation of the screen physical coordinates, which

I'll call chromium-POV-screen-physical-coordinates.

* There's no simple algebraic relation between the Windows-POV and

Chromium-POV screen physical coordinates like there is between

Screen DIPs and Screen physical on other platforms.

* For that reason, we always have to use the ScreenWin helper

functions to jump from internal Screen DIPS to the screen physical

coordinated Windows actually expect.

entry.content:

don't take resource multiplier, offset which yuv draw quad use for

libyuv conversion for simplicity. This is similar to how

GpuMemoryBufferVideoFramePool handles for copying buffers [1]
